Republican strategy to resist Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy with the need to combat electoral falsifications.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of electoral falsifications in the United States are more rare than cases of lightning deaths.
In addition, Republican lawyers have counted only 300 cases of electoral falsifications in the United States over a decade.
One thing can be said with certainty: these new trends will have a negative impact on the voter presence.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That’s why most state governments have since 2009 passed laws that complicate the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon gained a new scale after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo identity card and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of the will statement and take away the right to vote from citizens who have a conviction.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present an ID card with a photo.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law passed in Indiana.
The Republican authorities hastened to spread this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to present ID cards with photographs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people who have reached the voting age requirement, do not have a photo identity card issued by their state government agency.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required ID card often exceeds a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that is not all.
Students — voters who are believed to vote for candidates from Democrats — in several states are not allowed to use a photo identity card issued by their school.
However, these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mostly for Republicans, to use voting certificates issued by these clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin Americans.
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote for the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wish to register.
This restriction did not go without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the campaign to register voters helped to list about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
During the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of early voters were African Americans, although the latter made up only 13% of the state’s total voters.
The same thing happened with people from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they made up 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike the whites, who formed 76% of the voters, among those who voted early were only 46%.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended with the intervention of the U.S. Attorney General.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID card.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from Democrats have condemned the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing them as clearly aimed at influencing the outcome of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represented 171 out of the 270 votes needed in the college of electors to win the presidential election.
It is still too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is undoubted: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the voter presence.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Prostate cancer screening: to take a test or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes gives false results, false negative, and sometimes false positive, which lead to useless medical intervention.
Men, and so reluctantly undergoing dispensation, have something to doubt even more.
Testing or not?
I asked for the opinion of two experts.
In studies conducted in the United States, numerous cases of infection were observed among the subjects, so the data obtained is difficult to interpret and difficult to develop any clear recommendations.
Another study, this time European, found different rates of mortality in those patients who underwent screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, after 12 years of observation, that the likelihood of metastases was 30-40% higher in those who did not undergo screening.
Therefore, I would recommend taking a test starting at 50, or at 40, if one of the direct relatives had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also at increased risk.
The key point is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
Cancer can be both aggressive and sluggish.
The patient needs to clarify the degree of risk of his cancer, offering him possible options, without compulsory treatment of prostate cancer, which does not pose a danger to life in the long term, and making a choice, in these cases, in favor of active monitoring of the disease.
To date, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer will not undergo treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to life.
We will offer them active surveillance, and if the disease begins to progress, we will start treatment.
More and more often we are precisely defining the criteria for deciding who should or should not undergo a course of treatment.
So I would recommend going through the test.
But it is also important to consult with your doctor to determine whether or not to undergo this test.
