Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the news that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused a real upset — and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, neither much nor little.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted in the Standard Model — our best, or at least the “less perfect” description of the nature and behavior of matter — but which was previously unable to be detected by experimental means.
But physicists are not yet fully sure that it is precisely about the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of doubt, that we are dealing with a truly new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, the new data presented this week at one major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data are not yet sufficient for complete certainty.
Let’s imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, as the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what it means.
There is, in this world, one law absolutely inevitable, which states that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to bypass this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
But although elementary particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: the Pauli Exception Principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" lies, in general, in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens called the Fermions who prudently obey the Paulie Principle.
In another, the bosons, a disgusting gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything—at least for this principle, which means that they can rest in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of force", through which the main forces of nature are spread and to which in some way belongs the Higgs boson.
These same bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you are able to read this chronicle, it is due to one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “light particle,” which is the “courier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disturbs” the electromagnetic field in that particular place, like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" a electromagnetic wave (light, infrared radiation, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the "power carriers" bosons.
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken."
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the one in operation at CERN – the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! – is needed to such enormous energies.
An analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold onto the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like photons, by the way) do not have it.
So what can all these studies “bring,” Ms. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to perceive the discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of the SM.
In addition, some of them are passionate about the discrepancy, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to “new physics” and shut down some of the Model’s holes.
The latter, it should be said, still has substantial shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or dark matter that makes up about 80% of the universe (oh!).
However, such differences have not yet been found in CERN.
consequences
The benefit of these studies for the daily life of the average person is harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it does not exist.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell’s laboratories could not even guess what revolution their work would bring.
They anticipated their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at the Bell Laboratories, where laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were impulsive) in 1962, said that the laser was initially considered rather a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine it...
In addition, an application can be found for the instrument accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose at all, now serves as the "eye" for all digital cameras in the world and has earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that anything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die.
The Commission for the Dignity of Death in Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should be resumed soon, and at this time the bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
The debt tried to look closer.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. Still lived alone in his apartment in Monterey.
Prostate cancer, which destroyed him from the inside, gave him a two-year delay.
"I was given five years, I lived seven," he says, between life and death, lying in bed in the palliative care shelter of Victor-Gadboa in Beloi, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, it’s impossible to prepare for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that does not allow you to go to the toilet on your own and even eat on your own.
Sitting at the table where there is an appetizing lunch, he gives up and agrees to be helped to take food.
He gets alive, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicines, take him to the bath.
Courage before the ordinary death.
“My greatest desire to be cured of diarrhea is humiliating,” he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for this illness.
“Over the course of life, we are taught that a man should urinate standing,” says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadboa Shelter.
Regressing to the state of a child is an unbearable humiliation for some.
“It all depends on a person’s ability to accept decline,” he says.
Since, in the opinion of many people engaged in palliative care, important events happen at the height of this decline.
Patients who enter the Victor Gadbuya palliative shelter are all sick with cancer.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses no longer provides the help called “treatment.”
Ms. A., 89, is most afraid of dying “conscious of suffocation.”
But the illness allowed me to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t want anything more in life,” she says before allowing her to put on a breath-enhancing mask.
She is still waiting for her son’s last visit from Italy in the coming days.
In the Victor-Gadboa Shelter with the help of a group of volunteers provide body care and nutritional assistance.
This is the palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, for every 11,700 inhabitants there is one place in palliative care institutions.
This is very little, given that sooner or later we will all die.
Here life continues in the best conditions possible, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the shelter doctors.
Whether it is physical, emotional or mental comfort.
We will agree to give the dying a mouthwash of brandy or pepsi, depending on what he asks.
Diabetics are no longer forced to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought beer to Mr. X, who died tonight.
In the morning, his son drank this beer in the feet of the deceased.
“We help our loved ones as well as our patients,” says Natalie Savar, director of patient care.
In the shelter of Victor Gadboa, no day is like the previous one.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, laying on his pillows during a toast in his honour, a 36-year-old young man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children and has tried everything to survive.
“Over the past six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor Gadbuya shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is believed that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is provided to ease the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor Gadbuya Refuge and the Great Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, are more or less exclusively specialized in caring for cancer patients.
It is this huge gap in Quebec’s health care system that makes many palliative care practitioners fear the adoption of a law legalizing euthanasia and suicide assistance.
Starting in October, a manifesto signed by the lighthouses in palliative care, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Liapuant has been circulating, testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not efficient enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the ambulance, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I’m afraid that patients want to die just because they don’t get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists until the last day try to save patients, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Hope of survival for Ellen Richard was already minimal when she stopped exhausting chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was stopping the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered.
No full care.
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for not fulfilling their request after the palliative care team relieved their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsi Monroe, director of palliative care at the Great Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are not susceptible to pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about these sufferings.
More and more often patients who are unable to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients who suffer from pain always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to be easier.”
