Pay and sell without the help of banks – with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current exchange of money, based on central banks, numbered transactions between recipient parties c commission fees for their processing.
In addition, as often happens with these technologies, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current currency system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a nickname), is both a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euros ...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousands of sites accept bitcoin for donations or as a means of payment.
Bitcoin, which reached a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on the virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competing with the dollar or euro” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies as “credits” used to promote in a video game that are earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are simultaneously bookholders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is possible to check that the bitcoins used in the transaction really exist in a public billboard dispatched across the network.
The key step is the registration of a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which the solver, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the phase of file hashing, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers “take” a new transaction and add a number to it before “hashing” it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily check that it is correct.
The transaction is thus inseparably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If for the purpose of cheating a user would very quickly (in less than ten minutes) want to pay twice with the same subject money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed because they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly divided in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they can be divided into one hundred million, leaving a reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase of computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
"The defect used does not affect the protocol itself," says Pierre Nouza, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes real money payments using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Major players such as Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the billboard and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
The “giant sales” were announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works at Coinabul, which is engaged in the conversion of bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Nouza, another author of the tutorial on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which thus comes out cheaper.
The owner has better control over their personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, Pierre Nouza said, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
"Before Bitcoin is approved, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
In its report, the ECB proposes, by the way, to review the various risks that are now considered to be increased in the event of the system’s success.
