Difficult births of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a risky move by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever, on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, he decided to play a v-bank.
To surprise everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to finish the work.
It has been almost two years since Egypt relied on a preliminary text that has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions.
This new initiative only intensified the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President will persist in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "violate this word" and "destroy the law".
His followers in the camp are convinced that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their intention of explaining the text to the Egyptians, article by article.
For the president, this is also a way to restore social and democratic legitimacy, while discontent is bursting across the country.
Morsi seems to be convinced that Egyptians will vote in favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Times.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I reserve extraordinary powers,” which is expected to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday for the text.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked the door, feeling unable to convey their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society have done the same.
In order to reach the necessary quorum, 11 people, spare participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the articles were unanimously voted.
The commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around... the time for prayer, as some members of the committee considered that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was wrong.
The text on which the vote was held yesterday consists of 234 articles.
Object of general attention, Article 2 eventually remained identical to the article of the 1971 Constitution, which states that “the principles of Sharia are the primary source of law.”
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the basic requirements, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would enable their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” the liberals answer, who see this only as a pillar.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
In particular, they point to Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pomier, this is alarming, because "people called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy."
We can see the birth of the theocracy.”
Many liberals are also excited by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment there is no specific religious intervention.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas, but people with university education, some have been trained in the French system,” reassures Alexis Bleue, who is preparing a dissertation on Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that “around Article 220 there may be ambiguity, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to the “fiqh” [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise as to how competent civil judges are to make decisions about this.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is being criticized as it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they have decreased significantly compared to those under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the defense budget will not be considered in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
It will also not prohibit the trial of civilians in military courts, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider to be damaging to freedom.
Liability for blasphemy remains, and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and in particular for freedom of the press.
Furthermore, none of the articles is talking about protecting women anymore, emphasizes Heba Moraef, from Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, the demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will go to the streets on Saturday.
