Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the 20th member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the European Space Agency on September 12, 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in the following years took an active part in a number of ESA projects.
But Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
I will recall, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Cosmonautics" at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory.
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his "Introduction to Space Science".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 – 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known worldwide prophet of space, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the back of the moon was named in his honor.
In 1925 a railway was built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remains unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket was to be used to propel or to brake the truck.
Information about this dress is known only from the press of that era.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Section of weapons technology in cooperation with the professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mochitsky.
From the remaining materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter missile, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and in the following year the work "Airborne missile-torpedo and aviation missile-bomb" by the author Lelyva-Kzhivobloksky was published.
Both projects were developed for military use of missile engines.
Before the war, the Temporary Scientific and Consultative Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) co-ordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its activity the work ended due to the start of the war.
The following scientific work, devoted to cosmonautics, appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal "Problems", which publishes four volume articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will engage in cosmonautics.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining turnover, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the fall the POA became its actual member.
And the following year, the first Chairman of the PAA Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became the Deputy Chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish missile to perform scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of overcoming a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 the two-stage RM-2 missile was tested at the Bledovsk Pustyr.
This missile was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to engage in real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962 further development was suspended.
The successor of the first RM-type missile was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designed as Meteor-1A, -1V and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of flight for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aviation developed the Meteor-2 missile, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was able to take a useful cargo weighing 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Then the versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the Cospar (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the Cospar National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germanševsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
