Operation Argo: When the worst is nowhere, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist student protesters seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution to the United States, which had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the U.S. administration, a positive outcome of the situation was not expected - it could not afford to throw the Shah out of board, because this could fundamentally undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, it was unable to the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by a failed attempt to release hostages by force.
The prisoners were finally released after 444 days of negotiations with the mediation of the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iran sentiment at home.
The defeat in Iran largely contributed to Jimmy Carter’s defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, Operation Argo describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After a difficult journey, they ended their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them from Iran, and this was helped by the extravagant coverage legend, according to which they left on Canadian passports as members of the filming group, looking for a place in the country for the shooting of a science fiction epic.
Combination of Genres
The plan, which was invented by evacuation expert Tony Mendes, required collaboration from Hollywood.
In order for the legend to be credible, specialized journals wrote about the project of the film, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have long been kept secret, the film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, the real political thriller, the so-called "cinema-opus", the story of a successful event, an affair - an example can be a series of films about Oushen's friends.
The film is constantly changing moods - on the one hand, documentary scenes from Tehran (the titles show iconic historical photographs of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, eased Hollywood passages, intersecting with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in costumes discuss the situation at negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck made a reboot of his career.
From the ridiculous actor became a respected director, and his play ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third full-length film, after the dark detective Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye (2007) and the thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first film of Affleck that is not filmed in the director's hometown - Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place refers to the qualities that elevated the director's earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows this in Argo, where Tehran “playes” Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, while reconstructing real events – the entry scenes of the embassy’s fall impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when somewhere the story suddenly changes.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his colleagues in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters at the Tehran bazar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematographic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes thinking something — there it all goes out not so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents an imminent crisis at the airport in Tehran, and the pursuit on the runway look quite fictional).
The disadvantage of Argo is the dispersion associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it's a movie that can be watched with moderate interest, evaluating the production and retro-style, recreating the thrillers of the 1970s.
But it captures hard.
However, this is enough to remind us of one, still in a sense alive history, as well as to testify to how exaggerated the notions of omnipotent and omniscient intelligence are.
