Architects MVRDV prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Spikenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
"This building seems fun to me, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again," says Lysette Verhaig, walking on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, says, “No, this building is really beautiful.”
But I ask myself: Why do we need another library today?
Everyone has internet, iPads and e-books.
Nowadays no one volunteers to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spikenisse, a little notable sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 people has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance, several years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesque painted miniatures of iron concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had the only chance to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Vini Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, a master of bold column diagrams and the author of ingenious, sometimes even cynical constructions, treated the task with his usual restlessness and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his head and a smile on his face.
And while the members of the jury looked around confusedly and shrugged their shoulders, the bold Maas made a pyramid-size of his original gift and concluded his speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here is it, my suggestion: The Book Mountain in Spikenisse, the so-called Buckenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain worth 30 million euros has grown.
It is part of the revitalization project, which also includes a underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential houses and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the competition "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch national wood construction competition.
Thus, the faceless suburbs, which previously could offer nothing but a post-modern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, whose white facades suggest the idea of a milk factory, became richer by one modern work of architecture.
But most importantly - in Spikenis appeared the first in the history of this town public building of cultural purpose.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: book Eldorado under the cheese cap.
There is only one elevator passing through the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
The glassed room on all sides is light and easily visible, burned brick floors and elegant street lights create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly reconstructed.
The eye unwittingly looks for benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere – books, books, books.
“Typically, book shelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Vini Maas.
We put the classic configuration of space from foot to head and pulled out the reading area from the inside out.
The interior space of the book mountain is used skillfully: in the center there are offices, an internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical premises.
Especially delighted black book shelves, which serve as the decoration of the walls, the parapets, the staircases.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even experienced architects and construction engineers are lost in guessing what this unknown material is.
“We aimed to work with secondary materials,” explains Yop Trauborst, the project manager representing the Spikenisse community, in line with the requirements of the standard.
And once on an agricultural plant in Frisland we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fiber material millimetre thickness has been used as a base under the roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, after which it can be discarded.
For the library, this canvas – for the first time in such volumes – was pressed into a panel of four centimeters thick.
Under the action of heat and pressure, the so-called landscape plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a little like a new car and a little shoe.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Anyone who overcomes a path of almost 500 meters will be rewarded in the literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wooden ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the proper humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Costs of a new soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Troubort.
The heat of the earth is used for its heating and cooling.
Although Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun only gets inside for a short time.
Large wooden farms, perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take over most of the sunlight.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic rolling curtains.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig has also been here.
As well as lecturer of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogard, who called Buckenberg "the Spikenisse soul that was long missing."
A few weeks before the opening, each resident was invited to donate one book from his own assembly.
These books were supposed to occupy empty places on the shelves of the still not fully equipped library – at the time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are placed above.
“There is nothing worse than a semi-empty library,” says architect Vini Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation now every resident is somehow connected to this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it’s just for jewelry.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal task, which in professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Spikenise wrote his literary history.
They are very young and uneducated.
This is only the starting point for building identity.
Sabo: “Germans should play a more important role”
Germany abstained from voting on recognition of Palestine.
According to Stefan Sabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, Berlin balances on a narrow diplomatic path by doing so.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why is ?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO implemented this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is so.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely moving from the policy that, so to speak, was ruled by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a concerted common policy.
The Germans are once again between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that for now they are only perceiving their role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is the willingness to take a position in their national interests, independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests differ greatly from the interests of other major states, and therefore Germany must protect its own interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it needs to be careful not to insult the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its role.
But I’t attach too much importance to this, it’s not a completely unilateral connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relationship with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that she should be taken seriously as a player on the international arena and that her interests should be taken into account.
In Europe, there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the contrary, has clearly vetoed.
Is there a disagreement between the United States and many European countries?
Due to American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But in connection with the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that the substantial differences in opinions are not as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not entirely enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and its position as an important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would have been a little easier for the Germans if there had been a unified, non-contradictory European policy, but this is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot act within the framework of a broader approach and are forced to act instead, relying only on their own vision of the situation.
This is how they do with the euro.
I think that in the future, Germany will take on a leading role in developing a common European position.
It is clear that it is not easy for Germany, at least because of ties with Israel.
This topic has always been sensitive.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take on the main role?
Or is the leading role still hard to give to Germany?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to this, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis – every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
The Germans don’t just deal with it.
In fact, it’s an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to take into account the very different neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
So the influence of the United States in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don’t like it, it’s unpleasant, or it’s intensified by a lack of love for you – that’s life!
Stephen Sabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America jointly explore the problems of the transatlantic community.
He is also a member of the German Marshall Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
China's "trademark protection": when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-renowned trademark, Polo Ralph Lauren – too.
What is Armani Polo?
It is an officially registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the firms from whose names it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names file a lawsuit.
However, it is unclear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, which specializes in trademark infringements in the Far East.
Every week a new thing appears on my desk.
Simulators need to add just a few letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci is obtained Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way, German companies, such as the sports goods manufacturer Puma, are legally copied.
Pattloch opens a folder with records of the trademark registration office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, the Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also uses the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
The fact that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are multi-storey supermarkets that sell almost exclusively counterfeits.
However, the case of Pattloch is not so.On behalf of his trusts, he opposes that Chinese enterprises should officially obtain from the trademark registration office the right to use a name that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it “ban minpai”, a passenger brand.
This word is associated with “ban дакуань”.
This is what they call women who hunt for rich men.
Chinese authorities do not admit guilt
"This is damaging to business, it needs to be fought," Pattloch is convinced.
“The brand is blurred, the unique position is lost, the image suffers very much.”
Financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries are estimated at millions, especially in the case of expensive copying products.
According to market research firm CLSA, China is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods with sales of €15 billion per year.
However, removing dubious entries in the trademark register is difficult and expensive.
The process can take up to nine years, with an unclear outcome.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court rejected the lawsuits, as after a long time the contested name became "the reality of the market".
If the plaintiff fails, he will even have to pay the plagiarist because he has damaged his trademark in China, Pattloch says.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
There are also famous cases about graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a lawsuit with construction machinery manufacturer Sany, a company that acquired concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister shortly before.
Therefore, the Chinese still have the right to use the emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
The company that bought Volvo Geely originally used a blue-and-white logo that resembled BMW; the process was successful, Geely had to change it.
