Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the major sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial HPVs include syphilis, chlamydia and trippers (gonorrhea).
Common viral HPVs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes and hepatitis.
The lobular pediculosis and scabies belong to parasitic PTIs.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mostly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis registered in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low, but about 20 percent of new HIV infections fall into this group.
Chlamydia infections are significantly more common among young people than among other population groups.
According to European data, three-quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
The human papillomavirus is also common among young people.
How does the number of infections change?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are required to be registered.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the incidence of syphilis has more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2700 cases.
This is about one-tenth less than the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a venereal disease?
With infectious diseases, ulcers can occur in the genital area, complaints during urination, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as bubbles or seals.
However, they are often not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and remain unnoticed.
How can we protect?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
After all, in part, the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread by contact infection and by close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examination, especially with frequent change of sexual partners.
With early diagnosis, you can cure most illnesses and avoid distant consequences.
