Residents of Sweden (a long-standing rival, and not so long ago and a much more prosperous neighbor) come here to work.
The rackfish is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, though somewhat odorless, element of Norway’s past.
It is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here – a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you £9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in world news, and most inhabitants of the country seem to be happy with it.
People here still reluctantly mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who last year shot and killed 77 men, women and children.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called "July 22".
Norwegians find it very hard to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
Today’s well-being is driven by the growth (since the early 1970s) of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
“H, oil isn’t the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress, a woman with long, light hair and strikingly blue eyes, embodying Nordic well-being.
We are such a people, as you call it, reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks excellent English.
We don’t like to show up, we’re not glamorous.
Norway treats its oil very carefully – most of the revenue of the oil and gas industry is invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years before the global financial crisis, when everyone was plagued with money they didn’t have, Norway carefully calculated all the costs.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and go on hiking in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
“And there’s a rackfish,” she adds with a careless laugh.
I’m standing in the snow in a row for some food – I’ll have enough fish.
Here, a hamburger with salmon meat is definitely exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
My hotel holds a special dinner dedicated to shrimp, during which visitors vote for the best, or the most fragrancy, fish.
There is a direct TV show, which shows the host in a butterfly tie, surrounded by plates with a rackfish.
It is like the Eurovision Song Contest.
“So, Thor-Jurgen, what was your assessment for the best fish there in the mountains?”
“Yes, Howard, this is our assessment.”
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls from a chair, possibly by crossing the aquavite.
Or maybe just breathing the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto has a difficult start to his career.
As Mexican President-elect Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to look at the difficulties he faces and the mixed expectations of the people of his country.
Road traffic in Mexico is currently in a deplorable condition.
This city is overcrowded by transport and at its best, and steel fences have been erected since Monday, cutting several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from entering the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will wear the presidential tie and take over the rule of the country.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the government of Felipe Calderón, which is now taking office, but the country is plunged into a drug war that has taken about 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence," Mr. Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office of the White House.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to this goal.
Prior to such statements, alongside the U.S. president, Mr. Pena Nieto’s political career developed as governor of his native state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and extensive state surrounding the country’s capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
A straight man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, he is remembered with warmth.
Residents place it in the merit of revitalization of tourism, the development of the resort area and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Penya Nieto, which are strikingly different from the roads with pebbles and holes that were previously in this place.
Tables with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We’re linking him with hopes for real and serious change,” says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Penya Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We expect real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed in our country, primarily in the field of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was suppressed in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera acknowledges that after his 12-year absence in the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party puts great hopes on Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he denies the accusations of contentlessness raised by the opposition to the new president.
He is very straightforward and very dedicated to the realization of his vision for the future of the country.
He is a great politician and, above all, a man who can listen.
But in another part of the state, many people had a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nassau, also known as Ciudad Nessa, is the most striking contrast to the paved streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under the highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico itself.
And the problems in the municipality also have the harsh nature of this megacity.
Earlier this year, troops were deployed to humiliate the drug trafficking gangs in these areas; and violence against women is acute here.
In the desert near a vast landfill only in the last two years several dozen bodies of murdered women have been found.
More than a thousand women were killed in Mexico during the governorate of Mr. Peña Nieto—a figure far higher than that in the sadly violent city of Ciudad Juarez, whose name has become nickname when it comes to killing innocent women.
According to the opponents of Mr. Penya Nieto, in the best case, it can be said that during his tenure as governor he failed to cope with the problem of killing women.
In the worst case, his administration is accused of completely ignoring this problem.
An inhabitant of a concrete house similar to most of the houses in this crisp neighborhood, Ireneia Buendia struggles to hold back her tears by showing me pictures of her late daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes she was killed by her fellow resident.
“When I got to her house, it seemed like her body had been washed before,” Ms. Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the body was already clogged.
Mariana’s mother tells the story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to the crucifixion, on which is written only one word: justice.
This is what, according to them, was denied to this family.
“The state officials treated me as an old gossip, an unhappy violator of calm.
They want people to simply believe everything they say and remain silent.
But this is wrong, so it is not possible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around," she says.
Having worn the presidential tie on Saturday, President Penya Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violence-related crimes, and the new president has vowed to make this issue a priority during his reign.
“I hope he will be exactly the same president he was a governor,” says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Sidney are most afraid of.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to disprove Bradley Manning’s claims about poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, more attention was paid to Manning’s presence in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is demanding that the case be closed on the grounds that the conditions of Manning’s detention were brutal.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing thousands of secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution sought to prove that ordinary Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified materials in U.S. history, failed to use many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he said he suffered while in a military prison.
During a cross-interrogation at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor major Ashden Feyn said records of Manning's weekly visits by prison administration during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
A cross-interrogation as part of the examination of Manning's defence request to terminate the case on the grounds that his conditions of detention were cruel and sufficient punishment were carried out the day after Manning stated that while in custody he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of secret documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the website WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday’s hearing, Attorney Feyn and Manning reviewed reports that followed Manning’s visits by administration officials during his stay in Quantico Prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Feyn asked Friday about the reports, Manning admitted that he rated the prison administration’s treatment of himself as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized.”
The reports did not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Feyn says.
Manning replied that he expressed his oral concern about these issues and that the representatives of the administration who visited him discussed these issues with him and stated that they would deal with them, but did not record this in writing.
"They recorded 'no problems' (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't raise that topic in the conversation," Manning says.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about ill-treatment in January 2011 during a committee meeting that examined suicidal intentions, which he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that session he wanted to get rid of the “traumatic warning” regime and soften the conditions of imprisonment.
Military officials explained that a restricted detention regime – lower than the supervision regime to prevent suicide – was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay, that they can cancel the trauma prevention regime... that the level of my life improves, from my point of view,” Manning explained.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for two months before being transferred to prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait and that one day he lost consciousness due to the heavy heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not told how your fate is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to the base of Camp Arishan, to the size of my prison,” Manning said on Thursday.
“I thought I would die in that cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small chamber — at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day — in complete solitude.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, clothes, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime was prohibited by the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, his eyes were constantly beaten by the light penetrating outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned over in bed at night, he said he was being woke up and forced to turn his back.
Manning’s lawyer filed an official objection to Manning’s ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livingstone, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning check.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to questions from the judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from a guard’s order that he had to throw a blanket that could cover himself, but admitted that no one had explicitly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked last night because he tried to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning that he told the officer that he could use a coward's rubber or shrapnel to injure himself, but he did not.
That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, clothes and glasses were removed from the chamber.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to experience during his detention and will significantly shorten the term of detention in case Manning is found guilty by a military court, which should begin his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning to admit guilt for less serious crimes, and other charges to challenge as excessive.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, and the prosecutor is expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico in accordance with rules governing the detention of detainees with the strictest possible regime.
Among the charges, Manning was charged with involvement in the enemy, illegally facilitating the disclosure of data on the Internet, transferring national defense-related information, and theft of state property or documents.
If he is convicted on all points of the indictment, he may be threatened with life imprisonment.
My Crisis of National Self-Determination is the story of an American of Mexican origin.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarre believes that Mexicans of American descent are torn between two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico, I walked through the arrival corridor, approached the border control zone and stuck in place.
The signs indicated two rows: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and I was called Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conditional name, like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York consider themselves Italians.
Later I stopped on the complex design of “American of Mexican origin.”
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complicated structures.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
So I got my U.S. passport and got in the line for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The topics on the agenda of the two presidents’ meetings were immigration, drugs and trade.
President Penya Nieto was eager to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans would now, with the same success, be able to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to sign a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc similar to the European Union.
In addition, President Pena Nieto has promised to continue the war against the drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals have been made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a tough and old-fashioned issue.
Most Americans have never thought about the fact that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and under a gunshot of rifles forced its leaders to give up half of its territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only worth any U.S. official to speak out at least a word of criticism toward Mexico, in the press and among the elite of Mexican society, complaints are immediately distributed that Americans violate the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montesuma are filled with hostility.
At the same time, the most difficult is Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Americans of Mexican origin living in the United States.
Want to talk about insults?
They are enough.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country for themselves, and those for whom there are no opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for just one reason: at some point in their family history, someone – father or grandfather – had no chance of realizing themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often, they were Mexicans of a certain type - sluggish, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
In Mexico they see it differently.
Today, our lives are the embodiment of the American dream, we have studied in good schools and got a good job, but we must not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider its own.
The United States of America.
In addition, we know that most representatives of the Mexican elite and ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see in us a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as false Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they’t have left.
We would not find ourselves now behind the silk curtain, finding a full life in the United States, but losing our spiritual connections.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the U.S. as a child, and this reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans – Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Mexican Americans are offended.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my American acquaintances of Mexican origin do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best of the two worlds inevitably loses roots.
We are Americans in Mexico.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations were not already confused enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to re-establish relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-born Americans to work as some kind of ambassadors of Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends how beautiful this country is and how great it is to visit, and we could persuade political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Oh of course.
Nothing will come out.
Too many offenses in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the rise of corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
Sorry, but do it yourself, Amigos.
And that is fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-born Americans are still offended for how they recently treated their relatives in Mexico.
Yes is .
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is a lasting peace possible between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
It sounds like usual, meaningless disputes about who first started; many buildings have become ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of Israel’s capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly trapped in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the “Arab Spring” rounded up in the uprising storm many established realities, and the Palestinians and the Israelis failed to stay away from the whirlwind that shook the region.
Per as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope to get out of this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the situation does not give rise to optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, this week's clashes have only strengthened the positions of the forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which came to power in Gaza in 2007, will declare that they have forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million inhabitants locked up in one of the most populous and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing its popularity on the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas may well come to the conclusion that time works for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
The emerging regional leader Turkey, once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing states in the Persian Gulf.
Solemn Hamas supporters are announcing the creation of an Islamist moon around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the militant Hezbollah group, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Assad’s power, and further to Jordan, where the king’s authorities threaten Hamas’ allies.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region occurred at the southern borders of Israel, the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Mohammed Morsi was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the contrary, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more inclined to populism.
In future diplomatic settlements, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice will not even be silenced by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
Hamas was defeated militarily.
The Israeli anti-missile system Iron Dome justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas-launched missiles.
The citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, the United States has remained faithful to its unchanged stance; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the start of the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel’s economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that roughly 30 Israelis have been killed since 2004 by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide terrorists, partly through the wall that enters the West Bank – a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state – and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from the point of view of international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu’s position, whose Likud party – in preparation for the January 22 election – has joined with the even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of giving the Palestinians their own state?
If all the power on the West Bank is handed over to them, will they not start firing rockets from there toward Israel, as their fellow Gazans do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and hardly suppress any attempt to raise their heads.
Probably the hardline will win; however, their calculations may be disproved by the Arab Spring.
While the Islamists who are coming to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Launching a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to the same extent, must consider the long-term consequences of its policy.
As democratic changes in Arab countries begin, the deprivation of Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a delayed bomb that will sooner or later explode on Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression already undermines the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect – the growth of the Arab population – only aggravates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid for by the growing dissatisfaction of the international community.
Both sides need external impulse.
The only solution remains that is tirelessly called upon by reasonable representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and Israel’s concessions of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that a ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long since decided to halt arms supplies to Gaza, as well as Turkey and Qatar, have a more advantageous position than ever before to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, adopted since 1967, with a view to the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah movements.
That would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama should also play a role in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still shows reluctance to join the solution.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible if a peace agreement is reached between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the unified cigarette packaging law has entered into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and images of diseases affected parts of the body contrastingly stand out on dull green boxes, the same for all cigarette brands.
The first Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing logos and color designs of different brands with the same box of dull-olive colour with horrifying images of diseased body parts and images of children whose health is undermined by their parents' smoking.
In addition to the various pictures and inscriptions warning about the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packages, introduced in mandatory order from this Saturday - the names of brands, which are printed in the same small font.
These are the world’s toughest conditions for tobacco packaging.
The federal government of Australia says the goal of the measure is to keep young people from smoking by depriving this harmful habit of fashion status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
“It’s obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging,” said Tanya Pliebersek, health minister, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest share of smokers in the world, so these changes will not affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering the possibility of taking similar measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies say this will only increase the share of the black market, where cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This law will lead to serious consequences, different from those conceived by its initiators," said Scott McIntyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws promote business growth.
Sandra Ha, from a small family-owned company called Zico Import Pty Ltd, claims that the demand for port-cigarettes and silicone envelopes that hide unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (practically from scratch) since companies like British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a case in a high court in Australia two months ago, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, the company Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesale enterprises and is expecting a new batch.
This is a good business for us.
The potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the part of the population to which these measures are aimed.
After the adoption of a number of laws in Australia that made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and supporting them for sports events, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in prominent places, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from placing online advertising, but it cannot restrict foreign websites.
"If you're selling tobacco products and you only have that little hole left, the idea of promoting your product online will seem very tempting to you," explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of reviews of brands written on behalf of allegedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is it really the business of the ordinary citizen, who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he did not regret the effort and time and made the video, or is there a advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
Representatives of the tobacco industry have even taken measures such as sponsorship of Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims within the World Trade Organization, stating that trade has been subjected to unfair restrictions, despite the fact that trade relations of all these countries with Australia are very insignificant.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tania Pliebersek, the government has been discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first country to impose a mandatory photo warning about the harm of smoking.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening the laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia demonstratively do not obey the innovations.
These pictures do not touch me.
I just don’t pay attention.
"You just pick up a cigarette and hide the package in your pocket," explains Victor El Hague, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the package.
To be honest, the only thing that can make me give up is my little daughter.
James Yu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco store in downtown Sydney, claims that the same packaging has complicated the task of placing goods on the shelves.
"I used to have an hour to unload a new batch, and now it's four hours," he complains.
"The government should have taken and completely banned cigarettes, we would then say: what to do, okay, it's all over, we close the store," he says, lifting his hands up.
Missing in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our aircraft had mechanical problems and was replaced with another aircraft, which we were waiting for.
So I had enough time to reflect on the nature of boredom.
I will not deceive you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for the flight is really boring, and here neither books, nor magazines, nor iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help much.
Recently, however, more and more scientists and children’s development specialists have spoken in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations, missing is not so bad for us and our children.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass by us.
Per we need to strive for boredom?
Yes is.
And at the same time not.
We will return to that.
I used to think, like many, that boredom was a relatively recent invention, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom boasts a very ancient history," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii were found Latin inscriptions about boredom dating back to the first century.
At the same time, the question remains open about how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying research materials on this topic and asking a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people “want but can’t do something that would bring them satisfaction.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn’t do something they’d like to do.
With apathy, I don’t want to do anything.
The main thing about experiencing boredom, he says, is “the disturbance of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is running slowly.”
To describe boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and people who experience depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when we actually just have a hard time focusing on something.
In their study, “Unemployed Mind: Defining Boredom from the Point of Attention,” published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to a previous experiment, the participants of which listened to the recording of a voice reading the journal.
Some participants also heard loud sounds of an unrelated television program included in the neighboring room, others heard the same sounds at low volume, so that they could hardly be disassembled, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without a foreign soundtrack.
Those participants who heard low-volume television noted that they were bored, more often than others - they had difficulty concentrating, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to concentrate on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neurology at Guelph University, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, “for example, looking into the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom.”
It is believed, he continues, that when people begin to bend on a chair or draw carapace on a sheet of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions just help not to relax physically.
“The study showed that children who are not forbidden to swing and turn learn better and remember more information than children who are asked to sit down humbly,” says Professor Fenské.
At some point we all experience boredom: when a flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show different degrees of inclination to boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual characteristics, researchers developed a special "tendence scale to boredom".
Questions and statements are used to determine the score on this scale, such as "Many of the things I have to do are monotonous and monotonous" or "I am interested in too much, so there is no time for anything."
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys are more likely to miss girls, says Steven Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of Western Florida, especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
Adolescents are often missed.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he used a pager to connect with 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
32% of teenagers said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents say they are bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data would be about boredom now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “adolescence has a peak tendency to get bored,” mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let’s go back to my original question: is boredom useful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme manifestations it, as studies show, can push people to absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling, or abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to studying this problem.
“So our brains tell us to do something else; it’s boring,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this brain does not always know exactly what to do.
If you get bored and you turn that energy on playing the guitar or cooking experiences, you will do better for yourself.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and it will soon pass.
Therefore, if your child is missing and you give him an iPad, he will stop missing, but he will not learn to cope with boredom on his or her own or to manage his or her time and occupation in any other way.
"And such skills of independent regulation are used in very different situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to do something independently, he also learns self-control in general.
I don’t think boredom needs to be exaggerated.
However, considering it something bad is also not worth it.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with this.
“We see it so that we need to experience boredom more often, while boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In today’s world, we’re accustomed to the constant excessive stimulation of our senses,” he says, “and when there’s silence, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
It is still unclear how the new marijuana law will apply in Colorado.
Anthony Orosco, a nineteen-year-old football player and public college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with committing a criminal offence that will soon be completely legal throughout the state: keeping a small portion of marijuana and a tube in which he smoked it.
Mr Orosko says that one day in September he and his friends were in Lamar and were driving a car through the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer discovered marijuana in his car, Mr. Orosko was ordered to court for possession of drugs and possession of a drug device – minor offences for each of which a $100 fine was due – and a date for the trial was set.
“They treat us like criminals,” says Mr Orosko.
Is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that continues several weeks after Colorado voted to legalize small amounts of marijuana for entertainment, the settlement of hundreds of small lawsuits depends not so much on the law as on the place of the trial.
Accusations of minor marijuana-related offences have already been removed in hundreds of cases here and in the state of Washington, which has taken a similar measure.
Police stations have already stopped charging people aged 21 and older for holding small doses, which will be considered legal once the law comes into force in a couple of weeks.
However, in the more conservative districts of Colorado, prosecutors have decided to consider existing cases related to marijuana and are still being prosecuted for the possession of the drug.
At the same time, some cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous areas of the West, are voting to prevent the appearance of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their locations.
“It’s all going so fast that I don’t even know what to expect next,” says Daniel J. Oates, a police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Representatives of the control bodies in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They will have to formulate rules to determine the procedure for licensing the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say that Colorado, for good or for bad, outperforms most other states in regulating marijuana use, first for medical purposes, and now for entertainment.
"Colorado has a more orderly market, so they will serve as a good example," explains Brian I. Smith, a spokesman for the Council for Regulation of Alcohol Production and Sales in Washington State.
But now no one can do more, admits Mr. Smith, than to make suggestions and hope that it will work.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we could focus on,” he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will come into force on December 6 and will throw the state into a year-long state of uncertainty when the state’s licensing system is not yet in place and the right to possess marijuana is already legalized.
And there are still difficult technical aspects that need to be solved during this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order on "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on its trade at a distance of 1000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
“It will be difficult to place licensed marijuana within cities, in Seattle and its suburbs,” explains Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the recently established research group, the Centre for Marijuana Legalization.
On November 21, police chief Outs of Aurora emailed his subordinates that the city’s prosecutor’s office would no longer bring persons aged 21 to justice for possession of small amounts of marijuana, and that the police would stop accusing people of these violations “from now on.”
Police chief Oates said the police would monitor compliance in the city with the rules governing the activities of people who grow marijuana for medical purposes and will prosecute illegal drug dealers and distributors.
Prosecutor Ken Buck, of the Uleed County in northern Colorado, presents a stricter approach to the matter.
After voting on the bill, he said the prosecutor’s office would continue to prosecute for possession of marijuana, mainly to encourage people who use it to undergo treatment.
At the moment, 119 individuals have been charged with possession of two or fewer ounces of marijuana, although many of them are also charged with other violations.
“The obligation of our institution is to prosecute for acts that are considered criminal at the time they were committed,” Mr. Bak said in a statement.
The reaction was ambiguous even in places like the rural district of Mesa, where voters rejected the proposal to legalize marijuana.
Police in Grand Jankshn, the largest city in the district, no longer hold adults accountable for possession of small amounts of drugs.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to remove charges in cases already opened related to marijuana possession.
“I believe that ensuring compliance with the law until it changes is our direct duty,” he says.
Despite the fact that 55% of Colorado residents voted in favour of the decision, incorporating marijuana use for entertainment into the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the contradictory reaction of residents in different parts of the state revealed the ambiguity of the attitude of the local authorities to the state experiment with marijuana.
“The district prosecutors have a cultural barrier in this matter,” explains Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer representing convicts for marijuana holding and a local representative for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
“They have persecuted people for so long that they can’t really accept that it’s no longer a crime,” he says.
Colorado and Washington, the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana as much as alcohol, are destined to become a nationwide experimental field to test the very idea of legalizing drugs.
Supporters of legalization and state officials are planning to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time they are looking forward to instructions from the federal authorities, which are still planning to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Supporters of marijuana legalization hope that the Office of Justice will give in on this issue.
Despite several widespread arrests of traffickers and patients who used marijuana for medical purposes, the federal government has mostly favored the medical marijuana trade in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Drug Office agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to close their eyes on state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug advocate in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for federal authorities to act.
Even before the presidential election, some local governments approved a moratorium on opening new marijuana stores, which would not be able to open before a year later.
Last week, Montrouge, a city in the western part of the state, proposed a six-month ban on the trade in marijuana, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a situation where we give someone a license and then it will cause serious problems at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
The municipality voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still a lot of unresolved issues.
Petronella White: I was survived from Oxford for being a conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
As long as I remember, I’ve always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of the ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization – free-thought and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying at the University of Oxford’s Wooster College’s Faculty of History in the late 1980s, I picked up my suitcases and left, which turned out to be the first real scandal in my life.
My father could not stand and cried.
Friends were confused.
The Evening Standard that I left college because I didn’t like my classmates having sex in a neighboring room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I had to leave because I had to drink from the bottled cups.
In fact, it wasn’t so funny.
I have escaped.
Yes, I fled because I was systematically harassed and intimidated.
Not because of my rather unusual name or because I was in a private school.
I was poisoned for only one reason, and in this glorious cradle of enlightenment it looked like barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, now deceased Woodrow White, was a well-known adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the Conservatives.
You may ask, why remember this now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students who adhere to right-centered views are subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as those granted to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives from the Corpus Christi College student club in Cambridge say they are "often actively isolated, subjected to personal assaults and made to feel unwanted guests" because of their political views.
They want to introduce an additional representative to the College’s Equal Rights Committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only aggravated by the recent BBC 2 documentary about student politics "Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right", in which conservatives were presented by eccentricists and neo-Nazis.
The film showed Joe Cook, a former president of the Conservative Association of the University of Oxford, who rides a rolls-roye, wears a silver suit and a trunk with a silver trunk.
In other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made “the goats of dismissal because of higher tuition fees.”
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the Association of Conservatives at the University of Nottingham, said in an interview with a Sunday newspaper that “the university environment is increasing in the direction of left-wing views.
People who don’t even know us think of us as rude and unpunished children of wealthy parents.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student at Corpus Christi College, where the request for reinforcement was filed, calls the atmosphere “uncomfortable,” and Stephanie Cheryl, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association, says the attitude of members of the student club to right-centered viewers has deteriorated significantly.
“This poses a threat both to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and simply to the normal life of the club members,” she says.
For the first few weeks at Oxford, I was not just a minority, I was alone.
I arrived there in September 1986, a shy and shy eighteen-year-old.
Oxford was feverishly hated by the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university voted to deprive former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to cuts in budgetary appropriations for higher education.
In such an atmosphere, even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
In the first days of the first-class week, when students get to know each other and the teachers, I first felt what was ahead of me.
I didn’t know yet that the teachers not only looked through their fingers at the seduction of conservative students, but also took part in it with pleasure.
Political issues – miners’ strike, privatization, and the government’s refusal to impose sanctions on the apartheid government in South Africa – have penetrated through the wooden panel walls of audiences.
At my first seminar I had to translate the French text of the eighteenth century into English, and I was not prepared for what followed.
“Miss White,” said the teacher, now deceased Harry Pitt, “please translate the first paragraph.”
The text was difficult for me, I was locked up.
Harry Pitt was a very yellow man with a face that looked like a cake.
“The Tatcherists do not teach French in principle, or do they just lack brains?” he asked.
Other students were shaken.
I had tears in my eyes.
“I would advise you to take a few primary lessons of French in your free time, if you’re not very busy rotating in society,” Pitt said.
I went back to my room completely unhappy.
That evening in college I was sitting at lunch alone; then someone kicked me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year student from the Faculty of English, who presented himself as a member of the University’s Conservative Association.
“I know who you are,” he said friendly.
Unfortunately, the case is as follows:
Anyone who is suspected of sympathizing with conservatives will be mocked.
It’s not easy for me, but in your case they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it’s going to be harder for you.
Most first-class conservatives pretend to be Labourists.”
Later, in the local pub, I cowardly tried to hypocrite.
I insisted that I disagree with everything Margaret Thatcher says.
The trick failed.
A student at the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who studied at Iton, said, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contagious.”
Other students picked up his words.
I was broken, dirty.
“How do conservatives have sex? – One of them asked.
“They cheat each other, aren’t they?”
I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the abolition of prosecution in the 1960s.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or do I have to meet with the like-minded only under the cover of the night?
Will I be forced to become a Labourist and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years seemed like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for belonging to the Conservatives, but also for being Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of her speakers.
He hardly appeared in college.
He despised him for his provinciality, pettyness, and commitment to the Marxist-Determinist view of history.
In 1997, he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won’t be happy here,” he told me.
I moved to Oxford from my parents’ home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased friends in the capital.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He did not believe me.
During his studies in the forty years there were accepted any political views.
“But this is the best university in the world,” he said complainingly.
There is no such thing, except not in the city of sleeping spires.
Even my communist friends always behaved impeccably.”
His wet eyes blurred.
“Don’t make hasty decisions.
I am sure it is just a joke.
You’ll break my heart if you quit college.”
I was exhausted by constant trips to London and my emotional defense weakened.
My friend, also a conservative, did not withstand the pressure and abandoned his beliefs.
The next week, during a seminar, when another history teacher called me “the enemy of the people” very seriously, I decided to do the same.
Burning in my soul of shame, I confessed that “my parents were brainwashed,” and called them “old fools.”
The rest was not long.
The last nail in the cover of my Oxford career’s grave was destined to be struck by my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns each week for Rupert Murdoch’s publications.
My door was locked.
I didn’t go out, and five minutes later my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I picked up my suitcases and got on the first train to London.
I have never returned.
You can call me a puppy and a puppy.
But at eighteen, no one should be the object of such anger and intimidation in a school.
Even more sad, it was Oxford, which not only released the fourteen prime ministers of the Tory, but still hides behind the unmerited reputation of a university that values equality and free-thinking.
