The hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah-Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of a volcano along steep rocky paths.
There are people for whom their job is hell, while others literally work in hell.
Among them is Antó Vidjaja, one of the 400 miners who make a living by mining sulfur in the Kawah-Ijjen volcano on the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Antho descends to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes when it comes into contact with air.
Having cut out huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, rolls the baskets on his shoulders and carries them upward along a crumbling rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, whose height is 2,386 meters, only 250 meters, however, exhausted cargoers take more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle step, hardly keeping balance and carefully tapping the road, so as not to back down and fall from the breach.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as it happened to a tourist from France who crashed a few years ago from the rocks of Kawah-Ijen.
Miners from Kawah-Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once on the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys from the circus and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, step three kilometers to the weights that the mining company placed just above, at the height of 1,850 meters.
It’s about Pt Candy Ngrimby, an enterprise that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, better not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical industries, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make fireworks, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
“Since the norm is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each move,” explains Antó, who usually performs three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each of them and eventually feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11,5 euros) by the end of the day.
While it seems miserable for such an inhumane effort, it’s three times as much as he’d earn in the field.
“The miners’ salary is very high by local standards, where they pay 15,000 rupees (1,2 euros) per day for collecting coffee and the average monthly earnings are two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the carrier, who previously worked as a stone maker on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot wasn’t that heavy, but Antó returned with his family to Banyewangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason that in Indonesia is as devastating as gray: “I married a girl from Bali, where there are only Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam.”
Anto has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, constantly coughing, and he has tearful eyes due to toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Antó spent three years risking himself in Kawah-Ijen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, he constantly coughs, and he has tearful eyes due to the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
That’s the price he has to pay to his dream.
“I’ll work for another two years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this nice and clever young man could be a tour guide, waitress, or hotel portier, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing the dirty wooden cabin with other carriers, he wakes up every day at two o’clock at night, because the sulfur does not stop flowing out at night when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, Antó descends into the crater, illuminating his way with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought for his own money.
Around 400 carrier carriers pull baskets with gray on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don’t even get a portion of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) fee for photography, which, along with the entrance ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guard of this reserve charges tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its people-mules.
“This is a job for cattle, not for people,” says Badrusin, a 42-year-old rooted carrier who has spent three decades in Kawah-Ijen since leaving college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will tolerate the work "as much as he can" because he needs money to educate his three children aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches miners in the dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so enduring that no one complains about their severe illnesses... more serious, obviously, than their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pain, and shoulder ulcers that have deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unaynik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks carry to the warehouse in Tamanzari, overcoming a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow trail among the grains.
“I will not retire, I will die here, because a volcano is my whole life,” says Unnik, opening his mouth wide, missing a few teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest occupations in the world: what human mules from Kawah-Ijen do.
