UNASUR summit ends without the announcement of the Lima Declaration
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the announcement of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven binding participants.
Efe has repeatedly attempted to gain access to the document signed at the VI meeting of heads of state and government of the UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the main page that it would be transmitted after closure, but then confirmed that at a certain point it would be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
Asked about the text, they pointed out that the content was outlined by Peruvian President Olivia Umala during brief press releases.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited all the time.
During the day only was broadcast, in the press room, video of the presidential assembly without sound with the message "closed session, sound prohibited".
Few of the information that circulated among reporters was transmitted by the press secretaries of some of the UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian.
The only document spread over the course of the day was a list of participating presidents, which sparked the discontent of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian presidential administration sent a media email with the summit’s “final declaration”, but it was a statement by Umala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and at that time, despite the press’s insistence, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was not spread.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure transmission systems for all journalists, but limited the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also ended with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
Presidents of Peru, Olivia Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Piñera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they would comply with the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the statements of both sides, as part of the charges that Lima raised against Santiago.
"We will observe and enforce a decision that will clarify the disagreements we are currently presenting to this international court," Umala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," Pineera added, welcoming Umala with a handshake against the background of the two countries' flags.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will obey the International Court of Justice came immediately after Colombia protested this week against the Bogotá Pact, according to which it recognized obedience to the verdicts of that international court following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it found wrong.
The summit took place in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in the UNASUR was suspended since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Olya Umar, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, a little later in the afternoon at Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and directions of action were approved on 31 projects among South American countries, the amount of planned investments amounted to $ 17 billion.
Among the agreements he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the agreements on the place of residence."
He said that action is being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizens' uncertainty and organized transnational crime, action to increase access to medicines, affordable internet access in all corners of South America, and taking into account the risks of natural disasters in a combined and effective way."
As Europe is in crisis, "the economic union (of Latin America) should not have a triumphant foundation, but should serve to expand our production base and foresee a better future for our cities," Umar added.
“We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 flagship projects that will improve the connectivity of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes,” the Peruvian president said in a read message.
Among these projects he mentioned that five belong to Peru, and are limited by cross-axis on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united, and to have good relations between neighbors was another topic highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, Colombia’s President, Juan Manuel Santos, said before joining the regional meeting that he hopes to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to conduct respectful negotiations on the maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogota.
"After tomorrow, I may meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua," he said.
“With President Ortega, I hope to be able to tell him that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they are expected to attend the inauguration of the new president of the country, Enrique Pena Nieto.
In the framework of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc met preliminarily to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the participation of the latter is suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
