AIDS mortality today is the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when he was announced that his AIDS test was positive.
"I felt like I was stunned," he recalls that difficult, despite the whole tacit of the doctor, moment.
The young man hid it from his family.
Having decided to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn as much about it as possible.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" patients in the HIV department of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994, overcoming many obstacles.
He has been living with the diagnosis of "Human Immunodeficiency Virus" (HIV) for 22 years.In the early 1990s, it would be difficult to believe this - too few treatment options existed, too little was known about the disease, too prejudiced to patients.
So, even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Protection clinic did not want to say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
In other words, at that time, having AIDS was a sentence.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and do so without deteriorating the quality of life.
Nevertheless, not knowing about their illness, so far many people come when the virus has already done damage, "exhausted" their immune system, and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the AIDS outbreak in the world, at least after the first cases, “the great achievement at the moment is that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same,” said HCG’s head of HIV, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, referring to the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious scientist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but life expectancy and quality depend on the degree of damage to the immune system present in patients at the beginning of the diagnosis, with the best life expectancy in non-drug users: up to 30 years with 200 CD4s, and up to 50 years when 500 CD4s are.
Simply put, the above means that a person who gets a diagnosis of being HIV-positive at the age of 25, according to these terms, “will be able to live up to 75 years without problems byining control,” he explained.
To evaluate this progress, it should be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has dropped from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNEDS annual report), it is also true that since the advent of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In Haliko alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have already been recorded by May this year; nevertheless, it is claimed that there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
Why are there still fatalities?
I personally think that the problem is not access to treatment.
I think that’s what happens in our hospital.
At least the last 12 years we have not had a shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late because they are unaware of their infected state, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
He cited devastating data: “Nine out of ten patients come when they already have any opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make a diagnosis at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for detection on a large scale, for all people who will ask for it.”
In their proposal, experts and officials of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Haliko (COESIDA) agree, as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who turned to a private laboratory for examination only motivated by the fact that it was done by his friend and, despite his young age, he was already in the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and don’t want to know anything.
“If I’m going to die anyway, I’m better off fighting three times a week,” they say, but not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, do exercise, take medications.
So far, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life like anyone else.
“I work, I do a lot of work, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person,” said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to promote his statement to those who are now, in the context of World AIDS Day, experiencing fear.
Let them check if there was a risk of infection, let them find out as soon as possible whether they are HIV-positive, so better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them learn that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This message summarizes the theme of fighting AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the shelf
There are big gaps between health programs and the common citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who dealt with the HIV-related issue.
The biggest is prevention.
In places devoted to this task, "in fact, the spread of condoms has increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packs of a hundred, and this is very good, but it turns out that there are those who now still do not have access to condoms," he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"Why are they you?" is a popular question, with echoes and condemnations, from social workers, school consultants, pharmacy employees and health workers who don't want to hear teenagers, the propagandist assured.
I propose to change this inefficient distribution; that condoms be not just behind the shelves and that a hundred of them be in machines in public toilets in places that are frequently visited by young people.
This is not an encouragement of disintegration.
It’s not about paying for beer and a motel, Governor Emilio Gonzales replied when asked if it was possible to distribute condoms under his leadership.
"It's not sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who are already practicing sexual activity," he said.
Key data in Halisco
13,435 total cases (12,158 cases of AIDS and 1,317 cases of HIV) were recorded.
The state ranks 4th in the national ranking for new and total cases of AIDS and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections relate to the sexual pathway, 6% through the blood and 2% to the perinatal pathway.
